@*
    ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    BnPicker — Phase 7.3 Task 1.2 (design decision 3: THE STATE-OWNER
    PRECEDENT), authored in .razor.

    Emits the `select` element → NodeType 7 — "picker", on the wire since
    Phase 2.5 and a do-nothing stub in both shells until this phase. The
    LAST stubbed widget becomes real. Android: Spinner + ArrayAdapter. iOS:
    UIPickerView with the component as its own dataSource/delegate.

    Unlike input (where the TEXT lives in .NET and the widget echoes it), a
    native picker OWNS its items and its selection UI — that is what
    "state-owner" means, and why the wire ships the whole item list as data:

      • `items` prop — the item strings as a FLAT-JSON STRING ARRAY (the
        normative grammar lives in BnItemsJson.cs — the shells' strict
        parsers are written FROM that comment; malformed → log loudly,
        render empty). ALWAYS emitted — `[]` for null/empty — so the host
        prop exists from mount and no shell invents a default.
      • `selectedIndex` prop — the CLAMPED selection as an invariant int
        (see the clamp rule below). Always emitted.
      • `change` event — the EXISTING wire, payload the newly selected index
        as an invariant int. Unconditional attach + `enabled` semantics:
        BnCheckbox's (one prose home).

    ── THE CLAMP RULE (NORMATIVE — mirrored by both shells in Gates 2/3) ────
    A selection must always be valid against the CURRENT items:

      • Items empty            → selectedIndex is -1 (nothing to select; the
                                 only state an empty picker has).
      • Items non-empty        → selectedIndex clamps into [0, Count-1]:
                                 an item shrink below the selection clamps
                                 TO THE LAST item; a negative clamps to 0.
                                 (A native Spinner/UIPickerView always shows
                                 a selection — "unselected" does not exist
                                 on a non-empty native picker, so -1 is not
                                 representable there and is not a wire state
                                 for non-empty items.)

    The picker OWNS selection validity (the state-owner precedent), so when
    clamping changes the effective index away from the bound SelectedIndex
    parameter, the picker NOTIFIES SelectedIndexChanged with the clamped
    value — the bound .NET state re-syncs to what the native widget actually
    shows, instead of the echo and the screen disagreeing. The wire always
    carries the CLAMPED index, never the raw parameter. An IN-RANGE
    programmatic set re-fires nothing (the loop guard is untouched: the
    notify happens only when the clamp MOVED the value).

    THE NOTIFY FIRES ONCE PER DISTINCT (clamped, raw) PAIR (Gate 1 review
    I2). Termination must not depend on the parent writing the clamp back: a
    receiver that does not store it (or any bound component — its
    HandleEventAsync auto-StateHasChanges) re-renders the picker with the
    SAME out-of-range SelectedIndex, and re-notifying on every render is an
    INFINITE loop (clamp → notify → parent StateHasChanged → re-render →
    clamp → …). So the picker tracks the last-notified pair and stays silent
    while it repeats; a NEW raw value or a NEW clamp result (items changed)
    notifies again, and an in-range set clears the tracker.

    The same rule applies INBOUND: a change dispatch whose index is out of
    range against the current items (a benign shell/.NET race — the user
    picked just before an item-shrink frame applied) CLAMPS by the same rule
    rather than faulting; only a payload that does not PARSE as an invariant
    int is garbage → FormatException → rc 2 (the 7.2 pattern).
    ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
*@
<select items="@ItemsJson"
        selectedIndex="@EffectiveIndexWire"
        enabled="@(Enabled ? null : "false")"
        backgroundColor="@BackgroundColor"
        margin="@Margin"
        alignSelf="@AlignSelf.ToStyleValue()"
        flexGrow="@Grow.ToStyleValue()"
        flexShrink="@Shrink.ToStyleValue()"
        flexBasis="@Basis"
        width="@Width"
        height="@Height"
        minWidth="@MinWidth"
        maxWidth="@MaxWidth"
        minHeight="@MinHeight"
        maxHeight="@MaxHeight"
        position="@Position.ToStyleValue()"
        top="@Top"
        right="@Right"
        bottom="@Bottom"
        left="@Left"
        @onchange="HandleChange" />

@code {
    /// <summary>The strings to show. Null or empty means an empty picker.
    /// The text is opaque — commas, quotes and non-ASCII are all fine.</summary>
    [Parameter] public IReadOnlyList<string>? Items { get; set; }

    /// <summary>The selected index. It is always clamped to something valid
    /// before it reaches the platform: <c>-1</c> when <see cref="Items"/> is
    /// empty, otherwise into <c>[0, Count-1]</c>. When the clamp moves it,
    /// <see cref="SelectedIndexChanged"/> fires with the clamped value so your
    /// bound state matches what is on screen.</summary>
    [Parameter] public int SelectedIndex { get; set; }

    /// <summary>Raised with the newly selected index when the user picks — the
    /// write-back half of the <c>@bind-SelectedIndex</c> pair. It is <b>also</b>
    /// raised with the clamped index when a change to <see cref="Items"/> forces
    /// one, so your bound state never drifts from what the picker shows.</summary>
    [Parameter] public EventCallback<int> SelectedIndexChanged { get; set; }

    /// <summary>Set false to show the platform's disabled picker and stop it
    /// responding. Default true.</summary>
    [Parameter] public bool Enabled { get; set; } = true;

    // ── The flex ITEM surface (BnScroll's — how this leaf sits in its parent) ─

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.BackgroundColor"/>
    [Parameter] public string? BackgroundColor { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.Margin"/>
    [Parameter] public string? Margin { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.AlignSelf"/>
    [Parameter] public FlexAlign? AlignSelf { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.Grow"/>
    [Parameter] public float? Grow { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.Shrink"/>
    [Parameter] public float? Shrink { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.Basis"/>
    [Parameter] public string? Basis { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.Width"/>
    [Parameter] public string? Width { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.Height"/>
    [Parameter] public string? Height { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.MinWidth"/>
    [Parameter] public string? MinWidth { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.MaxWidth"/>
    [Parameter] public string? MaxWidth { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.MinHeight"/>
    [Parameter] public string? MinHeight { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.MaxHeight"/>
    [Parameter] public string? MaxHeight { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.Position"/>
    [Parameter] public FlexPosition? Position { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.Top"/>
    [Parameter] public string? Top { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.Right"/>
    [Parameter] public string? Right { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.Bottom"/>
    [Parameter] public string? Bottom { get; set; }

    /// <inheritdoc cref="BnView.Left"/>
    [Parameter] public string? Left { get; set; }

    private string ItemsJson => BnItemsJson.Write(Items ?? []);

    /// <summary>The normative clamp (file header), applied to
    /// <paramref name="index"/> against the CURRENT items.</summary>
    private int Clamp(int index)
        => Items is not { Count: > 0 } ? -1 : Math.Clamp(index, 0, Items.Count - 1);

    private string EffectiveIndexWire
        => Clamp(SelectedIndex).ToString(System.Globalization.CultureInfo.InvariantCulture);

    /// <summary>The last (clamped, raw) pair the state-owner notify fired
    /// for — the once-per-pair guard (file header). Null whenever the
    /// current SelectedIndex is in range.</summary>
    private (int Clamped, int Raw)? _lastNotifiedClamp;

    /// <summary>The state-owner notify: when the clamp MOVED the selection
    /// (items shrank below it, went empty, or a caller passed an
    /// out-of-range index), re-sync the bound state via
    /// SelectedIndexChanged. An in-range set clamps to itself — nothing
    /// fires (the programmatic-set-no-refire guard). Terminates BY
    /// CONSTRUCTION, not by trusting the parent: the notify fires once per
    /// DISTINCT (clamped, raw) pair, so a parent that writes the clamp back
    /// converges (the re-render is in range and clears the tracker), and a
    /// parent that does NOT write back re-renders into silence instead of
    /// the clamp → notify → StateHasChanged → re-render loop (Gate 1 review
    /// I2 — the pre-fix shape hung Mount itself).</summary>
    protected override Task OnParametersSetAsync()
    {
        var clamped = Clamp(SelectedIndex);
        if (clamped == SelectedIndex)
        {
            _lastNotifiedClamp = null;
            return Task.CompletedTask;
        }
        if (_lastNotifiedClamp == (clamped, SelectedIndex))
            return Task.CompletedTask;
        _lastNotifiedClamp = (clamped, SelectedIndex);
        return SelectedIndexChanged.InvokeAsync(clamped);
    }

    private Task HandleChange(ChangeEventArgs e)
        => SelectedIndexChanged.InvokeAsync(Clamp(ParseIndexPayload(e.Value?.ToString())));

    /// <summary>Strict wire parse — an invariant int. Missing or unparseable
    /// is a SHELL contract violation: throw (FormatException) → dispatch
    /// rc 2 (the 7.2 pattern). An out-of-range but well-formed index is NOT
    /// garbage — it is the benign items-shrink race, and the caller clamps
    /// it by the normative rule.</summary>
    private static int ParseIndexPayload(string? payload)
        => payload is null
            ? throw new FormatException(
                "picker change dispatch carried no payload — the wire contract requires " +
                "the selected index as an invariant-culture integer")
            : int.Parse(payload, System.Globalization.NumberStyles.Integer,
                System.Globalization.CultureInfo.InvariantCulture);
}
